1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:05,095
By January 1986, the space shuttle had

2
00:00:05,095 --> 00:00:07,158
flown 24 times.

3
00:00:08,120 --> 00:00:09,883
Each flight reinforced one idea.

4
00:00:09,923 --> 00:00:11,365
The system worked.

5
00:00:12,367 --> 00:00:14,040
Across those flights, engineers documented

6
00:00:14,040 --> 00:00:15,712
O-ring damage.

7
00:00:16,493 --> 00:00:18,707
Erosion, blow-by, hot gas pass seals

8
00:00:18,707 --> 00:00:20,922
designed to hold.

9
00:00:21,763 --> 00:00:24,448
Low-temperature flights all showed distress.

10
00:00:24,428 --> 00:00:26,251
But each flight survived, and the warning

11
00:00:26,251 --> 00:00:28,074
lost force.

12
00:00:29,155 --> 00:00:30,739
Danger became a known condition.

13
00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:33,382
A stop signal became a line item.

14
00:00:34,425 --> 00:00:36,188
The night before Challenger, engineers

15
00:00:36,188 --> 00:00:37,951
recommended against launch.

16
00:00:38,953 --> 00:00:39,975
The burden shifted.

17
00:00:40,034 --> 00:00:41,830
Instead of proving it safe to fly,

18
00:00:41,830 --> 00:00:43,627
they were asked to prove it was

19
00:00:43,627 --> 00:00:45,423
unsafe.

20
00:00:46,417 --> 00:00:48,307
On the coldest morning the program had

21
00:00:48,307 --> 00:00:50,198
ever faced, 73 seconds was all the

22
00:00:50,198 --> 00:00:52,088
physics needed.

23
00:00:52,149 --> 00:00:54,353
The warning was never missing.

24
00:00:55,295 --> 00:00:56,227
It had been made survivable for too

25
00:00:56,227 --> 00:00:57,159
long.

26
00:00:57,942 --> 00:01:00,527
Small causes, massive consequences.
